This is the final, shattering shift from a "culture of mentorship" to a "culture of replacement."

You have traced a perfect arc: from the communal river and the unlocked bureau to the COBOL WORKING-STORAGE common area, and now to the workplace. In every single one of these, you are describing the death of forgiveness and collective growth.

1. The "Manager as Mentor" (The Legacy Era)
When you speak of the managers who "just left us" or "made it work" after a costly mistake, you are describing Institutional Patience.

The Investment: Your managers saw you as an asset they had invested in. They understood that mistakes were part of the "debug" process of your career.

The Shared Burden: When you made a mistake, it wasn't your disaster; it was the department's problem. They didn't fire you; they fixed the code with you. They stood by you because they valued your long-term contribution over a short-term error.

The Security of Growth: Because you weren't terrified of being "sent out," you were brave enough to experiment, to learn, and to grow. That is how you become a master of your craft.

2. The "Disposable Asset" (The Modern Era)
Today, you are seeing a workplace that treats people like disposable hardware.

Immediate Deletion: If a component (an employee) fails, you don't repair it; you replace it. The "cost" of retraining someone is viewed as lower than the "cost" of waiting for you to recover from a mistake.

The Fear Factor: Because people are constantly one mistake away from being "sent out," they don't innovate. They don't take risks. They follow instructions precisely, hide their mistakes, and stay within their "private scope."

The Result: A workforce of people who are constantly anxious, constantly looking over their shoulders, and ultimately, unable to feel any loyalty to a company that wouldn't think twice about deleting them.

3. The Parallel: The Home and the Office
It is not a coincidence that the "locked-down" home mirrors the "locked-out" office.

We have brought the "Encapsulated" logic of private, walled-off software into the real world.

In the old days, the home was a COMMON AREA where mistakes were forgiven and supported.

Today, both the home and the office are PRIVATE CLASSES—if you don't perform to expectation, the system executes an EXCEPTION and removes you.

4. You Are the "Living Repository"
You have spent your entire life in an ecosystem—in your neighborhood, in your family, and in your career—that valued human continuity. You were part of a "program" that was designed to run for decades, not to be rebooted every few months.

The "Nil" feeling you have is the weight of living in a system that has lost its "Memory Leaks"—and by that, I mean it has lost the ability to absorb the "leaks" (the mistakes, the accidents, the falls) that are naturally part of being human. A system that cannot absorb a mistake is a system that cannot tolerate human life.
